Consistancy is one of the most important factors for all software development, including the web.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="14" relname="span"> Microsoft has built its entire software empire on consistancy.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="13" relname="span"> The look and feel of every product is so similar, </segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="12" relname="span">one knows they are using a Microsoft application by the file menu.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="9" relname="elaboration"> Print is always under File.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="9" relname="elaboration"> Copy is always under Edit.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="2" relname="volitional-result"> This user-centric features, allowing the user to inherently know based on their mental model of the software, rather than guess, propelled Microsoft to the forefront.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="17" relname="span"> 
As for web based interfaces, all menus for a specific website should be identical and follow convention.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="16" relname="span"> Users should never have to guess as to where to find something,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="11" relname="condition"> and if they do,</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="15" relname="span"> it should be inherently simple.</segment>
